---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Our Story"
  description="Who we are, why we went to New Zealand with kids, and why we built this guide."
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
    <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-forest-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">About Us</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Our Story</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 mb-10 leading-relaxed">
      We are a family that loves travel. New Zealand was the one we kept putting off. Then we stopped putting it off.
    </p>

    <div class="prose prose-forest max-w-none
      prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-gray-900
      prose-p:text-gray-700 prose-p:leading-relaxed
      prose-a:text-forest-600">

      <h2>Why New Zealand?</h2>
      <p>
        We had been talking about New Zealand for years - the kind of place you describe as a dream trip while quietly assuming you'll never actually go. The flight felt too long. The kids were too young. The timing was never right.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then the kids got older, the timing got right enough, and we decided the flight was going to be what it was. We booked three weeks and started planning.
      </p>

      <h2>What We Found</h2>
      <p>
        New Zealand is one of the most family-friendly places we have ever been. It has world-class scenery, endless outdoor activities calibrated for kids of every age, good food, a safe and easy-to-navigate infrastructure, and people who are genuinely glad you are there.
      </p>
      <p>
        It also has a 17-hour flight, a 17-18 hour time difference, and costs that require honest planning. We found surprisingly little content that addressed all of this from a family perspective - most travel guides are for adults, and most "family travel" content is generic.
      </p>

      <h2>Why We Built This</h2>
      <p>
        NZ With Kids is the resource we wish we had found when we were planning. Specific, honest, and written for families who want to do this right - not just survive the trip but have one of the best experiences of their kids' lives.
      </p>
      <p>
        We are not travel writers. We are a family who went, took notes, and came home wanting to go back.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
